Now that we have learned about four sections of a resume, let’s think about WHY we are writing one in the first place!<img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-44180" src="http://p2i.pyd.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/PYD_resumes3-e1515773796517.png" alt="pyd_resumes3" width="100" height="98" />
_________________________________________________________________________________
Another section on your resume is very similar to the work experience section: <strong>Volunteer Experience.</strong>

As a reminder, these are the sections of a resume:
<ol>
 	<li>Heading (personal information)</li>
 	<li>Objective Statement</li>
 	<li>Education</li>
 	<li>Work Experience</li>
 	<li><strong>Volunteer Experience</strong></li>
 	<li><span style="color: #808080;">Skills</span></li>
 	<li><span style="color: #808080;">Optional Sections</span></li>
</ol>
Many people writing a resume for the first time may have not had work experience before, but <em><span style="color: #ff0000;">volunteer experience</span> can be just as impressive to a potential employer!</em>
<blockquote><strong>Volunteer Experience</strong> – This section on a resume lists your most relevant volunteer experience as well as the skills and responsibilities you had in those positions.</blockquote>
What types of volunteer experience are good to include on a resume? Read the two following sentences and think about which one is more appropriate.
<ol>
 	<li>I would make a good salesperson because I once volunteered for an hour cleaning up trash in a park.</li>
 	<li>I would make a good salesperson because I spent two years volunteering in the concession stand of my high school, and this taught me how to have good customer service and deal with unhappy customers.</li>
</ol>
On your resume, the different volunteer experiences you include should be <strong>relevant</strong>. Relevant volunteer experience is considered to be:
<ul>
 	<li>Is long term (so more than just one time!)</li>
 	<li>Teaches you<em> transferable skills</em>.</li>
</ul>
Volunteer experience is an optional section for a resume. There are two reasons you would include a volunteer experience section:
<ul>
 	<li>You have <strong>relevant</strong> volunteer experience that will help you in your next job.</li>
 	<li>You want to show your commitment to service and diverse experiences.</li>
</ul>
_________________________________________________________________________________
There are <strong>two types</strong> of volunteer sections on a resume.

The FIRST we will call the <strong>“Expanded List”</strong> type. This is written exactly like a work experience section! Make sure it includes these components:
<ol>
 	<li>Name of the organization you volunteered for</li>
 	<li>Dates you worked as a volunteer (month and year)</li>
 	<li>City and state</li>
 	<li>Duties or responsibilities you had</li>
</ol>
Here is an example of an <strong>Expanded List</strong> format:

<img class="size-medium wp-image-44197 aligncenter" src="http://p2i.pyd.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/PYD_resumes3.1-1000x618.png" alt="pyd_resumes3-1" width="1000" height="618" />

Another type of volunteer position we will call the <strong>“Short List”</strong>.

Employers will still be impressed by employees who can give back and help others, so still include this information! If you do not have room on your resume or significant volunteer experience, your section might look like this:<img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-44198" src="http://p2i.pyd.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/PYD_resumes3.2.png" alt="pyd_resumes3-2" width="764" height="401" />

